  "prompt": "What is the difference between pollination & fertilization in flowering plants?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between pollination and fertilization in flowering plants:\n\nPollination:\n1. Initial stage of sexual reproduction\n2. Transfer of pollen grains from anther to stigma\n3. Occurs externally on the flower's surface\n4. Involves movement of male gametes\n5. Happens before fertilization\n6. Can be done by wind, insects, birds, or other agents\n7. Does not involve fusion of gametes\n\nFertilization:\n1. Final stage of sexual reproduction\n2. Fusion of male and female gametes\n3. Occurs internally within the ovule\n4. Involves actual fusion of sperm and egg cells\n5. Happens after successful pollination\n6. Requires specific cellular conditions\n7. Results in formation of a zygote\n8. Leads to seed development\n\nIn summary, pollination is the transfer of pollen, while fertilization is the actual fusion of male and female reproductive cells to create a new embryo.",
